{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568037","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568037"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:08:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:08:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19457"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19457","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19457"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.1,0.71,0.02,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12184"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84893"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"12184","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12184"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19457"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69172"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4267"},{"type":"tags","id":"4749"},{"type":"tags","id":"11501"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"28826"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28827"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28876"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34970"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84893","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/84893"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 50-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-year history of a lump behind his left earlobe. The lump has been slowly growing and occasionally discharges malodorous, white material. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a 2 cm firm, mobile, non-tender nodule on the posterior aspect of his left earlobe (Image). The overlying skin is intact with a small central dark pit visible. The surrounding skin shows no inflammation or erythema.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Keloid","Foreign body granuloma","Epidermoid cyst","Strawberry naevus","Lipoma"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of an epidermoid cyst, including a slowly growing subcutaneous nodule with a central punctum (pit) and intermittent discharge of malodorous material. \u003Cstrong\u003EEpidermoid cysts\u003C/strong\u003E are common benign lesions that develop from trapped epithelial cells, usually due to blocked pilosebaceous units. They contain keratin and lipid-rich debris that can have a characteristic cheese-like appearance and foul smell when expressed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKeloids\u003C/strong\u003E are raised, irregular, firm scars that extend beyond the original injury site. They would not have a central punctum or discharge material. Keloids are more common in people with darker skin and typically occur after trauma or surgery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eforeign body granuloma\u003C/strong\u003E would typically have a history of trauma or penetrating injury. While it might produce discharge, this would usually be purulent rather than cheese-like, and there would be no central punctum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Estrawberry naevus\u003C/strong\u003E (infantile haemangioma) typically appears in infancy, is bright red in colour, and would not have a punctum or discharge. These lesions usually involute by age 7-10 years.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELipomas\u003C/strong\u003E are soft, mobile, subcutaneous fatty tumours that do not have a punctum or produce discharge. They typically feel more rubbery and are often found on the trunk and proximal extremities.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Epidermoid cysts typically present with a central punctum and can discharge malodorous, cheese-like material.","Epidermoid cysts commonly occur on the face, neck and trunk, particularly in areas with numerous sebaceous glands.","The presence of a punctum is a key distinguishing feature of epidermoid cysts from other subcutaneous lumps."],"references":["Hoang VT, Trinh CT, Nguyen CH, Chansomphou V, Chansomphou V, Tran TTT. Overview of epidermoid cyst. Eur J Radiol Open. 2019;6:291-301. Published 2019 Sep 5. doi:10.1016/j.ejro.2019.08.003"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69172"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19457"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21537"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21537","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21537"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/Yof0px98gfoO9LQwagXCg7z7NDjA7C.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/Yof0px98gfoO9LQwagXCg7z7NDjA7C.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":490,"height":480}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69172","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/69172"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-12T19:53:33+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-12T19:54:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12184"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84893"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"dat